Drove down to the university 23 and checked on unit. It had gone down on high engine oil temp and was told to wash the cooler out as well. I shut unit down and locked it out and checked the cooler and it was terrible. I got inside and started cleaning it out. The top 2 sections I had to go over several times for how caked the dirt and bugs were on it and the bottom 2 sections were as bad but went over a few times to make sure it was good. Once it was all done I shut the door to the cooler and started unit up and monitored the oil and coolant temps. Once they got up to temps the oil temp was hitting 201 and the coolant was 198. I started checking the coolant valves to make sure they were good and I checked the oil temp sensor and harness to make sure they were good as well and they were. continued to monitor the temps and noticed that they would drop down when the coolant temp would get high enough and the thermostats would open. After a few minutes the temps would rise and drop back down. The oil temp was not getting over 205 and the coolant temps were still lower than the oil but no more than 5 degrees. Notified the customer on what it was doing and that I had cleaned the cooler and it had helped a lot that it was cleaned. Drove back to the pdogg and dropped the wash trailer off.

Got to the pdogg station and picked up the wash trailer and took it to the sugg station to fill up with water. Went back to the pdogg and shut unit down , locked it out and cleaned out the cooler while Mario assisted and watched the door and made sure if anyone came to let them know I was in the cooler washing it out. Once that was cleaned we started unit back up and the coolant temps still got up to 215 degrees. We shut the unit down and started checking around the coolant pipes and found the butterfly valve on to the main water pump was closed. We opened it up and checked to see if any more valves were not correct and found none. Started unit back up and monitored the unit and the coolant stayed around 198

Checked the ignition, fuel, and ignition systems. They were all working properly. Took off the reed valve housing to check the reed valves. Started up the unit and started with the PM. Checked all kills, checked dump controllers and dump valves, checked for leaks, checked ignition and fuel systems, read all gauges-verified that all readings were within parameters, set and record fuel pressure, check fuel injection system, check and adjust lube pumps, checked the governor. Drained the scavenger chambers, distance pieces, fuel tanks and compressor pulsation bottles, cleaned the air filters, replaced the spark plugs, inspected compressor valves and pressure packing, inspect all hoses, tightened up the belts, inspected all relief valves, cleaned & inspected all engine and compressor air breathers, greased all bearings. One of the pipe nipples that are in between the water pump and the coolant reservoir was leaking. The coolant was dark in color. Drained out the coolant. Replaced two pipe nipples and a pipe coupling. Filled up the cooling system with water. There was also a cooler tube that was leaking. Looked for the leaking cooler tube and plugged it. Cleaned and power washed the unit.  Started up the unit and got it back online.  Monitored the unit for 30 minutes.

whatWasFound: First stage packing gland was leaking
whatWasPerformed: Drove to location. Oil was dripping out of the compressor oil level controller candy cane. A bunch of pressure was coming out of the packing pot vent tube. Put down some diapers to soak up the oil. Blowdown and LOTO. Disconnected the lines going to the tube and it was the first stage that had a bad leaking packing gland. Connected tubing back up. Drained the oil in the compressor back to normal level. Removed the variable pocket and the doghouse doors on the first stage. Disconnected the tubing lines. Removed the packing lube assembly. Removed the piston. Removed the packing gland. Changed over the fitting to the new packing gland. Installed the gland and torqued to 35 pounds. Connected the tubing line and the lube assembly. Installed the piston with new polish tube after it was cross hatched. Installed the doghouse doors. And variable pocket. Disconnected the wires on the compressor oil level controller. Disconnected the tubing lines removed the oil level controller. Changed over the fittings. Installed the new oil level controller. Connected the tubing lines. Connected the wiring. Removed LOTO. Purged. There was gas pressure coming from the lube assembly on the first stage. Tried to tighten up the assembly but wouldn’t stop. Blowdown and LOTO. Changed the the nipple that goes into the packing gland. Reinstalled the lube assembly. Removed LOTO. Purged. Still leaked. Tried different combinations with the nipple and the top but still leaked. Called mark and believe the case has been cleaned up too many times and isn’t sealing properly. Will need a different packing gland. Headed in

First I met ryen at the Janie Connor so we could check out the differences in our turbos. Then we drove to the miss sue and pulled the air filter housing off revealing a split boot. I found a coolant leak in the main side over head coolant tubing that I had to repair by draining coolant out of the system, cutting and refitting the line, and filling the unit back up with coolant. I then used cat tools to check valve lashings on the rocker sets that were still attached. See attached picture for my findings. Adam met us with new push rods, so I replaced the broken ones, lubing all metal to metal surfaces as I went back together with it. I torqued the rocker tie down bolts to 200 then 330. Next I set valve lashings on the intake valves to .015” and exhaust valve lashings to .04” I reattached the ignition harness to its mounts on the head and found that the hole between cylinders 3&5 was missing its tie down rod. Next I put the split intake boot back on the cold side per suggestion by management until we get a replacement, placed the air filter housing back in its designated position and sealed the cracked intake boot to the best of my ability with silver tape. I then clamped down on the boot with its tie down bands. I released the unit from its lock out then cranked it. I heard what sounded like a slight chirp in the bottom end so I immediately shut the unit down and contacted management. When ryen arrived we cranked it again and we heard a brief knock that ceased before I could reach the e-stop button. Let the unit run as it was sounding good. Eventually loaded it up and ran it

whatWasFound: The tandem side packing gland was bad.
whatWasPerformed: Drove to location. Got info off panel and unit. Shutdown and blowdown. LOTO. I was on the tandem side and Chris was on the first stage side. Removed the variable pocket. Removed the bolts from the suction and discharge piping. Loosened the third stage cylinder bolts. Removed the third cylinder. Removed the doghouse door. Removed the Allen lock nut. Loosened the lock nut. Removed the pistons. Disconnected the packing oil lines. Removed the packing. Rebuilt the packing for the tandem side. Treybonned the cylinders to make sure they were clear. The packing kit for the first stage was the wrong kit and Chris had to put it back together how it was. Installed the packing gland and connected the lube lines. Switched to the first stage and helped Chris install the piston with the lock nut. Switched to the tandem side. Installed pistons with new rings and set the lock nut. Installed the third stage cylinder and tightened down. Installed the variable pocket. Rolled the engine over and it sounded like the cylinder was hitting something. Pulled a crank end valve and checked tolerances and adjusted on both sides. Removed LOTO. Purged and started unit. Checked lube rate and set for 15 to break in. Monitored and headed in
